WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.875 --> 00:00:05.380
Classical optimization is a crucial step in classical quantum algorithms

2
00:00:05.630 --> 00:00:09.634
like the variational quantum eigensolver or quantum machine learning.

3
00:00:10.010 --> 00:00:13.430
However, often it turns out to be difficult to minimize

4
00:00:13.430 --> 00:00:17.726
complicated functions in high dimensional parameters spaces.

5
00:00:18.226 --> 00:00:21.729
My name is Victoria Lipinska and in this video we'll explore

6
00:00:21.730 --> 00:00:26.067
classical optimization routines for classical quantum algorithms.

7
00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:29.571
Optimization problems are not easy.

8
00:00:29.571 --> 00:00:33.700
When the number of parameters grows, so does the number of possible

9
00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:37.871
combinations of values, and it grows exponentially.

10
00:00:38.329 --> 00:00:41.749
In chess, for example, there are 64 spaces

11
00:00:41.750 --> 00:00:46.755
and each player has 16 pieces after each player moves a single piece,

12
00:00:46.963 --> 00:00:53.803
there are 400 different positions. After two moves 72,084 positions,

13
00:00:53.803 --> 00:00:56.931
around 9 million after three and around

14
00:00:57.098 --> 00:01:00.643
280 billion after four moves.

15
00:01:01.227 --> 00:01:04.604
If we reach only 40 moves, the number of possible positions

16
00:01:04.604 --> 00:01:08.608
is estimated to be around ten to the power of 120.

17
00:01:09.025 --> 00:01:12.153
Playing a perfect game would require exploring all possible

18
00:01:12.153 --> 00:01:15.740
positions and this enormous growth means that going through

19
00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:18.535
all positions individually is unfeasible.

20
00:01:19.286 --> 00:01:24.916
This can be solved by breaking the problem into two smaller sub-problems.

21
00:01:25.126 --> 00:01:29.047
First, we need to determine which setups of the chessboard

22
00:01:29.255 --> 00:01:32.133
are likely to appear in future steps of our game.

23
00:01:32.383 --> 00:01:35.011
We'll call this our subspace of interest.

24
00:01:35.345 --> 00:01:40.141
And second, given that subspace, we must determine what move is best.

25
00:01:40.558 --> 00:01:42.227
We'll call this our best move.

26
00:01:42.894 --> 00:01:47.232
In this analogy, the initial search through the subspace of interest

27
00:01:47.482 --> 00:01:50.693
is the analog of our classical optimization algorithm.

28
00:01:51.277 --> 00:01:53.738
Once that subspace of interest is known,

29
00:01:54.030 --> 00:01:58.493
a quantum algorithm is usually responsible for finding the best move,

30
00:01:58.827 --> 00:02:01.788
given that subspace.

31
00:02:01.788 --> 00:02:04.165
Let's start with considering just one parameter,

32
00:02:04.165 --> 00:02:08.918
theta, parameterizing a cost function which we wish to optimize.

33
00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:12.382
If we plot the function, say it looks something like this,

34
00:02:12.882 --> 00:02:16.636
on the X-axis we have values of the parameter theta

35
00:02:16.803 --> 00:02:19.639
and on the y axis there's the cost function.

36
00:02:20.348 --> 00:02:24.185
Keep in mind the cost function could be an actual financial cost

37
00:02:24.185 --> 00:02:28.481
we wish to minimize or as is often the case in the variational quantum

38
00:02:28.481 --> 00:02:33.236
eigensolver, it could be an energy that is minimized by nature.

39
00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:36.364
Our objective is to find the theta

40
00:02:36.531 --> 00:02:38.575
that corresponds to the lowest cost.

41
00:02:39.367 --> 00:02:43.955
We start with an initial value of theta and in every optimization step

42
00:02:44.164 --> 00:02:47.542
we find a new theta that decreases the cost further.

43
00:02:48.168 --> 00:02:52.547
It seems like we know pretty easily which way to proceed on the graph if we're able to see it.

44
00:02:52.839 --> 00:02:56.676
But the difficulty in optimization is that we actually don't.

45
00:02:57.260 --> 00:03:00.763
We only find out the cost so a tiny piece of the whole puzzle,

46
00:03:01.097 --> 00:03:04.225
once we evaluate the function on the selected theta.

47
00:03:04.726 --> 00:03:07.353
This is the general way optimization works.

48
00:03:07.687 --> 00:03:11.858
The optimizer samples parameters theta and calculates the cost.

49
00:03:12.609 --> 00:03:16.613
As you can imagine, randomly choosing the parameter theta to reconstruct

50
00:03:16.613 --> 00:03:19.866
the whole topology of the function is not very efficient.

51
00:03:20.283 --> 00:03:23.536
Instead, what smart optimizers do is finding

52
00:03:23.536 --> 00:03:26.372
the gradient of the function in each step.

53
00:03:27.207 --> 00:03:30.501
This way the optimizer knows which direction on the plot

54
00:03:30.501 --> 00:03:33.630
to follow in order to find the smallest cost.

55
00:03:34.547 --> 00:03:38.176
Once the gradient is zero, the algorithm terminates,

56
00:03:38.176 --> 00:03:41.096
and the minimum is found.

57
00:03:41.096 --> 00:03:44.182
This minimum might not be the global minimum.

58
00:03:44.433 --> 00:03:47.185
It may be a local minimum,

59
00:03:47.186 --> 00:03:50.355
meaning it's the smallest value of the cost function in the neighborhood

60
00:03:50.647 --> 00:03:53.775
but not across the whole range of theta.

61
00:03:54.067 --> 00:03:56.945
In the case of one parameter, that's certainly possible.

62
00:03:57.195 --> 00:03:59.948
However, the more parameters we have,

63
00:04:00.156 --> 00:04:02.659
the more complicated the function becomes.

64
00:04:03.368 --> 00:04:06.663
Already, in the case of two parameters, we have a surface,

65
00:04:06.663 --> 00:04:09.999
and in the case of four, we can't even draw it anymore.

66
00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:14.545
Just like in the chess example, reproducing all possibilities

67
00:04:14.837 --> 00:04:17.839
quickly becomes intractable.

68
00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:19.716
We see that it's difficult to minimize

69
00:04:19.716 --> 00:04:23.554
complicated functions in high dimensional parameter spaces.

70
00:04:24.013 --> 00:04:28.685
However, to get reasonable results, we want classical optimization

71
00:04:28.685 --> 00:04:31.896
routines to be both fast and accurate.

72
00:04:32.730 --> 00:04:35.024
They also need to be robust to noise,

73
00:04:35.233 --> 00:04:38.945
which will have significant effect in near-term quantum computers.

74
00:04:39.821 --> 00:04:42.991
Classical optimization algorithms can be broadly divided

75
00:04:42.991 --> 00:04:47.161
into two classes - direct search and gradient based methods.

76
00:04:47.787 --> 00:04:50.915
Gradient based methods require information about the gradient

77
00:04:50.915 --> 00:04:53.751
of the function during the optimization process.

78
00:04:54.335 --> 00:04:56.629
This can either be computed analytically

79
00:04:56.629 --> 00:04:59.548
or approximated in a finite difference calculation.

80
00:05:00.257 --> 00:05:03.093
Direct search methods do not use gradient information

81
00:05:03.093 --> 00:05:06.096
and use other strategies to minimize the cost function.

82
00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:09.808
Some of the most commonly used optimization algorithms

83
00:05:10.058 --> 00:05:14.146
in the quantum computing landscape are the following optimizers.

84
00:05:14.688 --> 00:05:19.234
COBYLA stands for constrained optimization by linear approximation

85
00:05:19.234 --> 00:05:22.988
and it is a gradient-free optimization algorithm.

86
00:05:23.572 --> 00:05:28.911
SLSQP is sequential least squares programming,

87
00:05:29.161 --> 00:05:33.123
a gradient based optimization algorithm.

88
00:05:33.583 --> 00:05:35.835
It uses a stochastic perturbation vector

89
00:05:36.044 --> 00:05:40.298
to simultaneously compute an approximate gradient of the cost function.

90
00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:43.885
In a noiseless environment, optimizers like COBYLA

91
00:05:44.093 --> 00:05:47.930
and SLSQP were found to converge faster than SPSA.

92
00:05:48.681 --> 00:05:51.184
Classical optimizers have their own parameters

93
00:05:51.184 --> 00:05:55.480
that you can specify for particular cases, for example, step size.

94
00:05:56.022 --> 00:05:59.150
Those can typically be found in documentation related

95
00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:01.194
to the specific optimizer.

96
00:06:01.569 --> 00:06:05.323
I encourage you to check the references list below for a comparison

97
00:06:05.615 --> 00:06:08.201
of the most up to date classical optimizers.

98
00:06:09.077 --> 00:06:11.371
Let's explore one more phenomenon connected

99
00:06:11.371 --> 00:06:14.457
to classical optimization of parameterized quantum circuits.

100
00:06:14.916 --> 00:06:19.544
As we saw before, a vanishing gradient of the cost function can indicate

101
00:06:19.545 --> 00:06:24.634
that the optimizer ended up on a plateau with no interesting features, a so-called

102
00:06:24.634 --> 00:06:26.010
"barren plateau."

103
00:06:26.010 --> 00:06:29.555
A barren plateau can be a result of many factors.

104
00:06:29.972 --> 00:06:33.476
The gradient of the cost function corresponding to a quantum circuit

105
00:06:33.476 --> 00:06:35.770
with randomly initialized parameters

106
00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:39.524
decays exponentially to zero with the number of qubits.

107
00:06:39.941 --> 00:06:43.444
This is because the quantum space explored by the optimizer

108
00:06:43.611 --> 00:06:48.032
becomes exponentially large when the number of qubits increases.

109
00:06:48.866 --> 00:06:53.579
The ways to tackle this problem include reducing the number of parameters

110
00:06:53.579 --> 00:06:56.624
and therefore the dimension of the underlying space.

111
00:06:57.542 --> 00:07:00.837
Another way to think of the origin of the barren plateau issue

112
00:07:01.087 --> 00:07:04.632
could be the problem agnostic nature of the parameterized circuit

113
00:07:04.966 --> 00:07:08.261
faced with exponentially large parameter space.

114
00:07:09.387 --> 00:07:12.098
Designing a circuit in the way tailored to the considered

115
00:07:12.098 --> 00:07:14.350
problem could be a good solution.

116
00:07:15.184 --> 00:07:18.896
Besides the exponential parameter space that induces barren plateaus,

117
00:07:19.230 --> 00:07:21.858
other physical phenomena can also generate them:

118
00:07:22.358 --> 00:07:25.987
the noise and decoherence present in the quantum computing experiments,

119
00:07:26.237 --> 00:07:29.657
the overall expressibility of the parameterized circuit,

120
00:07:29.866 --> 00:07:34.454
or nonlocality and degree of entanglement of the cost function modeled.

121
00:07:35.329 --> 00:07:39.125
It remains an active area of research to address these challenges.

122
00:07:39.959 --> 00:07:43.753
Having now reviewed the principal components of VQE,

123
00:07:43.754 --> 00:07:46.841
we'll summarize the algorithm in the next video.
